04528nam a22006495i 9781503604070DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036040707 a10.1515/97815036040702doi  a(DE-B1597)563881  a(OCoLC)1198930791  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJK516b.P595 2018 7aPOL0400102bisacsh04a352.23/509732231 aPonder, Daniel E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPresidential Leverage :bPresidents, Approval, and the American State /cDaniel E. Ponder. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the Modern Presidency00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and tables -- tAcknowledgments and Debts -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Presidents, Approval, and Trust -- tChapter 3. The Quest for Presidential Leverage -- tChapter 4. Measuring Presidential Leverage -- tChapter 5. Presidential Leverage and the Creation of Public Policy -- tChapter 6. A Refuge of Low-Leveraged Presidents -- tChapter 7. Conclusion -- tAppendix A. Index of Presidential Leverage (IPL) by Quarter, 1961-2016* -- tAppendix B. Models with Approval and Divided Government -- tAppendix C. Significant Public Policies Used in Chapter 5, Figure 5.1 and Table 5.1* -- tAppendix D. Variables for Centralization Analysis in Chapter 6 -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor scholars, pundits, the public, and presidents themselves, presidential approval is an evergreen subject. Its actual impact, however, is often unclear: all too frequently approval is reported in a vacuum, dissociated from the American state writ large. Presidential Leverage reaffirms the importance of this contested metric. By situating approval within the context of public trust in government, Daniel E. Ponder reveals how approval shapes presidential strategies for governing, providing a useful measure of the president's place in the political system. The leverage that presidents derive from public opinion exercises considerable influence on their incentives and opportunities for action. Though it is more tenuous and fragile than the authority they derive from the Constitution or the law, it makes certain kinds of executive action more attractive at a given time. Using a quantitative index of presidential leverage, Ponder examines this contextualized approval from John F. Kennedy's administration through Barack Obama's, showing how it has shaped presidential capacity and autonomy, agenda setting, landmark legislation, and unilateral action. His analysis sheds light not only on the complexities of presidential power, but also on a broad swath of national politics and the American state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aExecutive powerzUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxPublic opinion. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 0aPublic opinionxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aAmerican "state". 4acentralization. 4apolitical capital. 4apoliticization. 4apresidential agendas. 4apresidential approval. 4apresidential legacy. 4atrust. 4aunilateral action. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Executive Branch.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360407040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604070.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles